  "texts": [
    "A preliminary overview of methodological approaches and sources is offered in Table 3.As already acknowledged, surveys distributed to platform governance teams, civil society groups, journalists and citizens can gauge expert and public perceptions of online information quality changes (e.g.",
    "due to transparency improvements under Article 13 and 24).",
    "Combining the survey results with field and lab experiments that directly manipulate exposure to misinformation before vs. after DSA roll-out can help quantify impacts on recipients while also capturing subjective attitudes and experiences [139,185].",
    "Surveying the European Board for Digital Services per Recital 134 could provide additional insights.",
    "For instance, experiments exposing groups to misinformation across platforms before and after DSA adoption, coupled with surveyed perceptions of its prevalence, would enable richer assessment.Computational analyses like dynamic computational models quantifying the diffusion patterns of known disinformation narratives across platforms and time periods can be enriched through multi-faceted qualitative data [122,138]."
  ]
}